# Phase 1 — Auth & Doc Correctness

Small, high-leverage fixes. Aim: one PR.

## Task 1.1 — Middleware: `getSession()` → `getUser()`

**File:** `src/middleware.ts:38-39`

**Why:** `getSession()` reads cookies and trusts the local JWT signature without revalidating against the auth server. Supabase docs explicitly warn against using it for server-side route protection. `getUser()` round-trips to the auth server and catches revoked sessions, password changes, etc.

**Change:**
```ts
const {
  data: { user },
} = await supabase.auth.getUser();

if (!user && !isPublicRoute) {
  return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/login", request.url));
}

if (user && isPublicRoute) {
  return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/dashboard", request.url));
}
```

**Validate:**
- `bun run build` passes
- Manual: log in, navigate to /dashboard → no redirect. Log out, navigate to /dashboard → redirected to /login. Navigate to /login while authed → redirected to /dashboard.

## Task 1.2 — Move Supabase env vars into `lib/env.ts` schema

**Files:**
- `src/lib/env.ts` — add fields
- `src/middleware.ts:13-18` — use `env`
- `src/lib/supabase-server.ts:5-11` — use `env`
- `src/services/supabase.ts:3-9` — use `env`

**Why:** The whole point of `lib/env.ts` is fail-fast validation at boot. Right now Supabase URL/key are checked at runtime in three places, each with its own error message.

**Caveat:** `services/supabase.ts` runs in the browser (it's the browser client), so it can't import the server-only `lib/env.ts`. For browser code, keep the existing direct `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` access in `services/supabase.ts` — do NOT touch that file. Only touch `middleware.ts` and `lib/supabase-server.ts`. The validation in `env.ts` will still catch missing vars at server startup, which is enough — Next.js inlines the same vars into the client bundle at build time.

**Note on `next.config.ts` (Task 1.3 below):** `next.config.ts` also can't import `lib/env.ts` because it executes before module resolution is set up and has no `server-only` boundary. Task 1.3 reads `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` directly — that's intentional, not a regression from this task.

**Change to `src/lib/env.ts`:**
```ts
const envSchema = z.object({
  // ...existing fields...
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL: z.url(),
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY: z.string().min(1),
});
```

Then in `middleware.ts` and `supabase-server.ts`, replace the runtime check with `env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` / `env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY`.

**Validate:**
- Build passes with vars set
- Build fails fast with a clear error if either var is missing (test by temporarily renaming in `.env.local`)

## Task 1.3 — Read CSP Supabase URL from env

**File:** `next.config.ts:10`

**Why:** `connect-src 'self' https://jpcflgphtkkqtbqmksdc.supabase.co` hardcodes one Supabase project. Staging or PR previews on a different project will have all Supabase calls blocked by CSP.

**Change:**
```ts
const supabaseHost = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL ?? "";

// inside securityHeaders:
{
  key: "Content-Security-Policy",
  value: [
    "default-src 'self'",
    "script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'",
    "style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'",
    "img-src 'self' data: blob:",
    "font-src 'self'",
    `connect-src 'self' ${supabaseHost}`,
    "frame-ancestors 'none'",
  ].join("; "),
}
```

**Validate:**
- Build passes
- Open DevTools → Network → confirm a request to Supabase succeeds without a CSP violation in the console

## Task 1.4 — Reconcile RLS doc vs. reality in CLAUDE.md

**File:** `CLAUDE.md` lines covering "Database conventions" and "Quality Checklist"

**Why:** CLAUDE.md says *"All queries account-scoped via RLS (no manual user_id filtering in app code)"* — but the actual code in `services/jobs.ts` and `services/profile.ts` correctly does manual user_id scoping, because Prisma connects as the postgres role and bypasses RLS. The doc is wrong, not the code. A future contributor will trust the doc, skip the manual scoping, and ship an IDOR.

**Decision required from Justin:** which story do you want to commit to?
- **(A)** Keep manual scoping in services. RLS is defense-in-depth only, applied to direct supabase-js queries. (Recommended — minimal change, matches current reality.)
- **(B)** Switch to a request-scoped Postgres role + `SET LOCAL request.jwt.claims` so Prisma actually enforces RLS. (Significant work, real per-row security.)

**If (A), update CLAUDE.md:**
> Replace "All queries account-scoped via RLS (no manual user_id filtering in app code)" with:
> "All service-layer queries must explicitly filter by `userId` from `requireAuth()`. RLS policies in `supabase/rls-policies.sql` exist as defense-in-depth for any direct supabase-js calls (not used by Prisma)."

Also remove the "RLS policies enforce account isolation in Supabase" line from the Quality Checklist or rephrase it as "manual user_id scoping in services + RLS defense-in-depth."

**If (B):** out of scope for this plan; open a separate plan document.

**Validate:** `grep -n "RLS" CLAUDE.md` shows updated language, no contradictions remain.

