# Phase 4 — Profile Child-Row Stability

The hardest phase. Replaces the destructive `deleteMany` + `createMany` pattern with a stable upsert/diff. Depends on Phase 2 (zod-validated IDs). One PR.

## Task 4.1 — Decide ID source

The current client generates `crypto.randomUUID()` for new rows in `experience-section.tsx:63`, `education-section.tsx:55`, `skills-section.tsx:49`. The server then discards them and Prisma generates `cuid()`. Pick one:

**Recommended:** server-generated. The client sends `id: undefined` (or omits `id`) for new rows; the server assigns `cuid()` and returns the full saved profile. The parent (`profile/page.tsx`) already overwrites local state with the server response after save, so the temp UUIDs naturally get replaced by canonical cuids on the next render.

**Schema change required:** in **this PR** (Phase 4), update `ExperienceSchema`, `EducationSchema`, `SkillSchema` from Phase 2.2 so `id` is `z.string().optional()`. This means Phase 2 lands with `id: z.string()` (required, matching the current client which still sends randomUUIDs), then Phase 4 loosens it to optional and removes the client-side UUIDs in the same PR. The two changes must ship together — do not loosen the schema in Phase 2 or you'll have a window where the server accepts ID-less rows but the client still sends them anyway, which is harmless but confusing for reviewers.

## Task 4.2 — Refactor `upsertProfile` to a stable diff

**File:** `src/services/profile.ts:143-216`

Replace the destructive block with a three-way diff per child collection:

```ts
async function syncExperiences(
  tx: Prisma.TransactionClient,
  profileId: string,
  incoming: Experience[]
) {
  const existing = await tx.experience.findMany({
    where: { profileId },
    select: { id: true },
  });
  const existingIds = new Set(existing.map((e) => e.id));
  const incomingIds = new Set(incoming.filter((e) => e.id).map((e) => e.id!));

  // Delete rows that are no longer present
  const toDelete = [...existingIds].filter((id) => !incomingIds.has(id));
  if (toDelete.length > 0) {
    await tx.experience.deleteMany({ where: { id: { in: toDelete } } });
  }

  // Upsert each incoming row
  for (const e of incoming) {
    const data = {
      profileId,
      type: e.type,
      title: e.title,
      organization: e.organization || null,
      startDate: fromIsoDate(e.startDate),
      endDate: e.isCurrent ? null : fromIsoDate(e.endDate),
      isCurrent: e.isCurrent,
      description: e.description || null,
    };
    if (e.id && existingIds.has(e.id)) {
      await tx.experience.update({ where: { id: e.id }, data });
    } else {
      await tx.experience.create({ data });
    }
  }
}
```

Repeat for educations and skills (skill is simpler — only `name` to compare).

Then in `upsertProfile`:
```ts
return await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  const profile = await tx.profile.upsert({ ... });

  if (data.experiences !== undefined) {
    await syncExperiences(tx, profile.id, data.experiences);
  }
  if (data.educations !== undefined) {
    await syncEducations(tx, profile.id, data.educations);
  }
  if (data.skills !== undefined) {
    await syncSkills(tx, profile.id, data.skills);
  }

  const fresh = await tx.profile.findUnique({ ... });
  if (!fresh) throw new Error("Profile not found after upsert");
  return toProfileData(fresh);
});
```

**Why a transaction is still needed:** the diff is read-then-write across multiple statements; without `$transaction`, two concurrent saves could each compute the same delete set and double-apply.

