# Sprint 1 Code Review — Remediation Plan

> **IMPORTANT:** This plan document is for reference only. Do NOT commit this file. `docs/plans/` is in `.gitignore`.

**Goal:** Resolve the issues identified in the Sprint 1 code review on branch `chore/code-review`. Out of scope: anything in the password-reset flow (forgot/reset password) and anything email-delivery-related — those will be addressed in a separate Sprint 2 plan.

**Scope note — what is excluded:**
- Reset password middleware bug (#23)
- Rate limiting forgot/reset password (#25)
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL` fallback in reset email (#26)
- Email PII redaction in logger (#6)
- Supabase email confirmation flow verification (#8)
- Forgot/reset password form duplication (#31, #32)

Everything else from the review is in scope here.

**Working branch:** `chore/code-review` (already created). Land this work as 5–7 small PRs, one per phase, so each is reviewable in isolation.

---

## Phase ordering rationale

Phases are ordered so each phase compiles and ships independently, and so the most important fixes (auth correctness, input validation, doc/reality reconciliation) land first while you still have the review fresh in your head.

1. **Phase 1 — Auth & doc correctness** (small, high signal)
2. **Phase 2 — Input validation everywhere** (largest phase, blocks Phase 4)
3. **Phase 3 — Logging hygiene** (small, mechanical)
4. **Phase 4 — Profile child-row stability** (the hardest, depends on Phase 2)
5. **Phase 5 — UX bugs and dead UI** (settings password, DatePicker, dashboard)
6. **Phase 6 — Cleanup, naming, dead code** (mop-up, do last)

---

# Phase 1 — Auth & Doc Correctness

Small, high-leverage fixes. Aim: one PR.

## Task 1.1 — Middleware: `getSession()` → `getUser()`

**File:** `src/middleware.ts:38-39`

**Why:** `getSession()` reads cookies and trusts the local JWT signature without revalidating against the auth server. Supabase docs explicitly warn against using it for server-side route protection. `getUser()` round-trips to the auth server and catches revoked sessions, password changes, etc.

**Change:**
```ts
const {
  data: { user },
} = await supabase.auth.getUser();

if (!user && !isPublicRoute) {
  return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/login", request.url));
}

if (user && isPublicRoute) {
  return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/dashboard", request.url));
}
```

**Validate:**
- `bun run build` passes
- Manual: log in, navigate to /dashboard → no redirect. Log out, navigate to /dashboard → redirected to /login. Navigate to /login while authed → redirected to /dashboard.

## Task 1.2 — Move Supabase env vars into `lib/env.ts` schema

**Files:**
- `src/lib/env.ts` — add fields
- `src/middleware.ts:13-18` — use `env`
- `src/lib/supabase-server.ts:5-11` — use `env`
- `src/services/supabase.ts:3-9` — use `env`

**Why:** The whole point of `lib/env.ts` is fail-fast validation at boot. Right now Supabase URL/key are checked at runtime in three places, each with its own error message.

**Caveat:** `services/supabase.ts` runs in the browser (it's the browser client), so it can't import the server-only `lib/env.ts`. For browser code, keep the existing direct `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` access in `services/supabase.ts` — do NOT touch that file. Only touch `middleware.ts` and `lib/supabase-server.ts`. The validation in `env.ts` will still catch missing vars at server startup, which is enough — Next.js inlines the same vars into the client bundle at build time.

**Note on `next.config.ts` (Task 1.3 below):** `next.config.ts` also can't import `lib/env.ts` because it executes before module resolution is set up and has no `server-only` boundary. Task 1.3 reads `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` directly — that's intentional, not a regression from this task.

**Change to `src/lib/env.ts`:**
```ts
const envSchema = z.object({
  // ...existing fields...
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL: z.url(),
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY: z.string().min(1),
});
```

Then in `middleware.ts` and `supabase-server.ts`, replace the runtime check with `env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` / `env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY`.

**Validate:**
- Build passes with vars set
- Build fails fast with a clear error if either var is missing (test by temporarily renaming in `.env.local`)

## Task 1.3 — Read CSP Supabase URL from env

**File:** `next.config.ts:10`

**Why:** `connect-src 'self' https://jpcflgphtkkqtbqmksdc.supabase.co` hardcodes one Supabase project. Staging or PR previews on a different project will have all Supabase calls blocked by CSP.

**Change:**
```ts
const supabaseHost = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL ?? "";

// inside securityHeaders:
{
  key: "Content-Security-Policy",
  value: [
    "default-src 'self'",
    "script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'",
    "style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'",
    "img-src 'self' data: blob:",
    "font-src 'self'",
    `connect-src 'self' ${supabaseHost}`,
    "frame-ancestors 'none'",
  ].join("; "),
}
```

**Validate:**
- Build passes
- Open DevTools → Network → confirm a request to Supabase succeeds without a CSP violation in the console

## Task 1.4 — Reconcile RLS doc vs. reality in CLAUDE.md

**File:** `CLAUDE.md` lines covering "Database conventions" and "Quality Checklist"

**Why:** CLAUDE.md says *"All queries account-scoped via RLS (no manual user_id filtering in app code)"* — but the actual code in `services/jobs.ts` and `services/profile.ts` correctly does manual user_id scoping, because Prisma connects as the postgres role and bypasses RLS. The doc is wrong, not the code. A future contributor will trust the doc, skip the manual scoping, and ship an IDOR.

**Decision required from Justin:** which story do you want to commit to?
- **(A)** Keep manual scoping in services. RLS is defense-in-depth only, applied to direct supabase-js queries. (Recommended — minimal change, matches current reality.)
- **(B)** Switch to a request-scoped Postgres role + `SET LOCAL request.jwt.claims` so Prisma actually enforces RLS. (Significant work, real per-row security.)

**If (A), update CLAUDE.md:**
> Replace "All queries account-scoped via RLS (no manual user_id filtering in app code)" with:
> "All service-layer queries must explicitly filter by `userId` from `requireAuth()`. RLS policies in `supabase/rls-policies.sql` exist as defense-in-depth for any direct supabase-js calls (not used by Prisma)."

Also remove the "RLS policies enforce account isolation in Supabase" line from the Quality Checklist or rephrase it as "manual user_id scoping in services + RLS defense-in-depth."

**If (B):** out of scope for this plan; open a separate plan document.

**Validate:** `grep -n "RLS" CLAUDE.md` shows updated language, no contradictions remain.

---

# Phase 2 — Input Validation Everywhere

This is the largest phase. Goal: every API route validates its body with zod and returns 400 on failure. One PR.

## Task 2.1 — Add a shared `validateBody` helper

**New file:** `src/lib/validate-body.ts`

```ts
import "server-only";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import type { z } from "zod/v4";
import { ApiError } from "@/lib/api-error";

export async function validateBody<T extends z.ZodTypeAny>(
  request: NextRequest,
  schema: T
): Promise<z.infer<T>> {
  let raw: unknown;
  try {
    raw = await request.json();
  } catch {
    throw new ApiError(400, "Invalid JSON body");
  }
  const result = schema.safeParse(raw);
  if (!result.success) {
    throw new ApiError(400, z.prettifyError(result.error));
  }
  return result.data;
}
```

**Why a helper:** keeps every route consistent (one error format), and lets `handleApiError` continue to be the single funnel.

## Task 2.2 — Add zod schemas to `src/types/`

**New file:** `src/types/schemas/job.ts`

```ts
import { z } from "zod/v4";

export const JobStageSchema = z.enum([
  "Interested",
  "Applied",
  "Interview",
  "Offer",
  "Rejected",
  "Archived",
]);

export const CreateJobSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().trim().min(1, "Title is required").max(200),
  company: z.string().trim().min(1, "Company is required").max(200),
  location: z.string().trim().max(200).optional(),
  stage: JobStageSchema.optional(),
  priority: z.boolean().optional(),
});

export const UpdateJobSchema = CreateJobSchema.partial();
```

**New file:** `src/types/schemas/profile.ts`

```ts
import { z } from "zod/v4";

const IsoDateString = z
  .string()
  .regex(/^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}$/, "Expected YYYY-MM-DD")
  .or(z.literal(""));

export const ExperienceSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string(),
  type: z.enum(["EMPLOYMENT", "PROJECT"]),
  title: z.string().trim().min(1).max(200),
  organization: z.string().trim().max(200),
  startDate: IsoDateString,
  endDate: IsoDateString.optional(),
  isCurrent: z.boolean(),
  description: z.string().max(5000),
});

export const EducationSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string(),
  institution: z.string().trim().min(1).max(200),
  degree: z.string().trim().max(200),
  fieldOfStudy: z.string().trim().max(200),
  startDate: IsoDateString,
  endDate: IsoDateString,
  gpa: z.string().trim().max(10),
});

export const SkillSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string(),
  name: z.string().trim().min(1).max(100),
});

export const ProfilePatchSchema = z
  .object({
    firstName: z.string().trim().max(100).nullable(),
    lastName: z.string().trim().max(100).nullable(),
    email: z.email().nullable(),
    phone: z.string().trim().max(50).nullable(),
    location: z.string().trim().max(200).nullable(),
    headline: z.string().trim().max(200).nullable(),
    summary: z.string().trim().max(5000).nullable(),
    targetRoles: z.array(z.string().trim().max(100)).max(50),
    targetLocations: z.array(z.string().trim().max(100)).max(50),
    workModePreference: z.enum(["Remote", "Hybrid", "On-site", "Flexible"]).nullable(),
    salaryPreference: z.number().int().min(0).max(10_000_000).nullable(),
    professionalLinks: z.record(z.string(), z.url()).nullable(),
    experiences: z.array(ExperienceSchema).max(50),
    educations: z.array(EducationSchema).max(50),
    skills: z.array(SkillSchema).max(200),
  })
  .partial();
```

**New file:** `src/types/schemas/auth.ts`

```ts
import { z } from "zod/v4";

export const CredentialsSchema = z.object({
  email: z.email(),
  password: z.string().min(1),
});
```

These can live as a single barrel `src/types/schemas/index.ts` if you prefer. Match existing barrel-export conventions in `src/types/index.ts`.

## Task 2.3 — Wire schemas into routes

**Files & changes (illustrative — apply the same pattern to each):**

`src/app/api/jobs/route.ts` POST handler:
```ts
const data = await validateBody(request, CreateJobSchema);
const job = await createJob({ userId: user.id, ...data });
```

`src/app/api/jobs/[id]/route.ts` PUT handler:
```ts
const data = await validateBody(request, UpdateJobSchema);
const job = await updateJob(id, user.id, data);
```

`src/app/api/profile/route.ts` PUT handler:
```ts
const data = await validateBody(request, ProfilePatchSchema);
const profile = await upsertProfile(user.id, data);
```

`src/app/api/auth/login/route.ts` and `register/route.ts`:
```ts
const { email, password } = await validateBody(request, CredentialsSchema);
```
Remove the manual `if (!email || !password)` checks — zod handles it.

## Task 2.4 — Drop unsafe casts in services

Now that body shape is guaranteed:

**`src/services/jobs.ts`** — make the cast unnecessary by tightening the input types:

```ts
import type { JobStage } from "@/types/job";

type CreateJobInput = {
  userId: string;
  title: string;
  company: string;
  location?: string;
  stage?: JobStage;       // was: string
  priority?: boolean;
};

type UpdateJobInput = {
  title?: string;
  company?: string;
  location?: string;
  stage?: JobStage;       // was: string
  priority?: boolean;
};
```

Then at lines 44 and 65, drop the `as JobStage` from `STAGE_UI_TO_PRISMA[data.stage as JobStage]` — it becomes `STAGE_UI_TO_PRISMA[data.stage]`. The Prisma stage type is still pulled from `@prisma/client` so keep `as PrismaJobStage` only if `STAGE_UI_TO_PRISMA`'s return type isn't already `PrismaJobStage`. Check the constant definition in `src/constants/job-stages.ts` first; if it returns `PrismaJobStage`, drop that cast too.

**`src/services/profile.ts:94`** — remove `as Record<string, string>` cast on `professionalLinks`. Zod now guarantees the shape, but the type stored in `Profile` is `Json` (Prisma) which Prisma maps to `unknown` on read. You'll still need *one* cast to `Record<string, string> | undefined` here because Prisma has no way to know the JSON shape — but it's narrowing-after-validation, not blind coercion. Add a one-line comment explaining why the cast is safe (zod validated on write).

## Task 2.5 — Update tests

**Files:**
- `src/tests/api/jobs-id.test.ts`
- `src/tests/api/profile.test.ts`

Add test cases for the validation path. Pattern:
```ts
it("returns 400 when body is missing required fields", async () => {
  const res = await PUT(makeRequest({}), context);
  expect(res.status).toBe(400);
});

it("returns 400 when stage is invalid", async () => {
  const res = await PUT(
    makeRequest({ title: "x", company: "y", stage: "NOT_A_STAGE" }),
    context
  );
  expect(res.status).toBe(400);
});
```

The existing happy-path tests should keep passing — zod is permissive of the shapes they already send.

**Validate phase 2:**
- `bun run test` — all tests pass, new validation tests pass
- `bun run type-check` — no `as` casts left in services for the touched fields
- Manual: `curl -X POST /api/jobs -H 'cookie: <session>' -d '{}'` → 400, not 500

